// p71 — Type aliases dispatch to the underlying type's methods
// (v3.12.0).
//
// `type Name = T` declarations were registered in `Sema::typeAliases`
// since v2.x but only used for generic-param erasure (`T → Any`).
// Real aliases — `type Headers = Map`, `type IntList = List`,
// `type Age = Int` — were defined but never dereferenced at use
// sites: `h: Headers := Map()` landed `h` in scope as "Headers",
// Codegen looked up an unknown type and fell back to an opaque
// shape, and `h.put(...)` either errored at Sema (`Unknown method
// 'String.put'`) or returned garbage at runtime (`h.length()` on an
// empty Map reading the wrong slot and printing 8).
//
// v3.12.0 dereferences the alias to its target at variable-binding
// time in checkVarDecl, AND rewrites the AST's typeAnnotation field
// so Codegen — which reads it verbatim for LLVM-type lookup —
// sees the canonical type. Both pieces are required: the scope
// dereferencing makes Sema's method lookup work; the AST rewrite
// makes Codegen allocate the right LLVM struct + dispatch through
// the right method table.
//
// Limitation: this release covers value-side aliases (Map, List,
// Int, Bool, etc.). Aliases over String (`type Name = String`)
// run into a pre-existing Codegen edge case in the top-level
// VarDecl path that's unrelated to alias work and queued for a
// follow-up.

// Need at least one non-VarDecl statement first to dodge the
// pre-existing Codegen edge case on first-AST-node string bindings.
print("p71 start")

type Headers = Map
type IntList = List
type Age = Int

h: Headers := Map()
h.put("a", "1")
h.put("b", "2")
print(h.length())         // = 2
print(h.get("a"))         // = 1

xs: IntList := [10, 20, 30]
print(xs.length())        // = 3
print(xs.get(1))          // = 20

age: Age := 42
print(age + 1)            // = 43
